<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09078i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09078i">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09078i"> 78(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> DMP Watch / bulky / axe rattle lamp / felt hat</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>By the Way</b> The announcement of the &ldquo;cut&rdquo; in the pay of the <mark>D.M.P.</mark> makes it of interest to refer to their predecessors, the <mark>Watch</mark>, or as they were more generally known, &ldquo;<mark>the Bulkies</mark>,&rdquo; who, for many years before 1838, when the present force came into being, looked after the peace and order and lamps of the then much circumscribed city. The old police were attired in loose trousers, roughly-cut tunics; they wore high <mark>felt hats</mark>, carried a contrivance something like a <mark>pickaxe</mark> for defence purposes and for dealing with the <mark>oil lamps</mark>, and each possessed a <mark>rattle</mark> to give the alarm if an attack was made on him while going his rounds. <small> <a name="FJ29feb24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FJ29feb24"><cite title="source">Freeman's Journal</cite></a> (29 February 1924) 8/5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
